detail.title: P2P's Voluntary Exit from Crescent's Active LSV Set
detail.description:
**Proposal Summary:**
P2P, a dedicated and established liquid staking validator on Crescent Network, has opted to voluntarily withdraw from the active liquid staking validator set. This decision comes after a thorough evaluation of the current economic sustainability concerning P2P’s operations within Crescent. Despite this departure, the camaraderie and professional respect between P2P and Crescent Network remain undeterred, and future collaborative endeavors are anticipated with eagerness.

**Transition Period:**
A one-month withdrawal period will be instituted for delegators to transition smoothly in light of P2P’s departure from the validator set. This period will ensure that delegators have ample time to reallocate their stakes to other validators within the Crescent Network, maintaining the network’s stability and continued operation.

Voting YES to this proposal means confirming P2P to be erased from Crescent’s LSV

As soon as this proposal pass, P2P will be erased from Crescent’s LSV group automatically. For the confirmation proposal, existing LSVs need to participate in voting.

detail.title: Proposal for Continued Support for the Crescent Academy
detail.description:
**Proposal:**

We submit this proposal to seek the Crescent Community’s continued support for the Crescent Academy. Over the past six months, the academy has shown significant progress in community building and educational reach, indicating a positive trend for future growth and engagement.

1. **Highlights and Achievements:**
The Academy has distributed 200,000 $CRE to community members, with the Discord user base growing by 40%, and engagement tripling since November 2022. The Zealy Quest Initiative and the formation of the "Elders" group have notably contributed to these developments, boosting content quality and participant engagement.
2. **Budget Allocation:**
We propose a budget of 180,000 $CRE (~$4,200 USD) for the next six months from the Community Pool(Currently 75,650,030 CRE). This amount will be distributed as rewards to active participants. We commit to reassessing and adjust the rewards based on any $CRE price fluctuations post product launches.
3. **Future Plans:**
We aim to boost content production related to Crescent and the broader Cosmos ecosystem and introduce quests that promote the use of Crescent products and services. This will not only enhance community interaction but also boost visibility and use of our offerings.
4. **Benefits:**
With continued funding, we can consolidate our community, increase Crescent’s visibility on social media platforms, introduce valuable quests related to DEX and the FLIP / Bootstrap module, and attract new users. This will not only drive traffic to our DEX but also cultivate a community interested in Crescent and the Cosmos ecosystem.

By voting YES to this proposal, you secure the future growth and success of our community. We appreciate your support in helping us realize the Crescent Academy’s full potential.

The Crescent Academy Funding will be managed by the Foundation’s multi-sig wallet(cre1u9jxn6l7seq5jjej4w6etpdxufphwfuunljr4e)

For detailed information about this proposal, please visit: https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/11841-proposal-for-continued-support-for-the-crescent-academy

detail.title: Increase the Deposit Amount for Crescent Governance - Parameter Change
detail.description:
# Increase the Deposit Amount for Crescent Governance
 *Authors:* [Simply Staking](https://twitter.com/SimplyStaking)

## Current Overview

Over the past couple of months, the network has been hit by a constant stream of 'spam' or 'malicious' proposals. As validators and community members alike, we have been constantly voting NoWithVeto (NWV) to ensure that the proposer's tokens are burned.

Currently, the cost to put a proposal on-chain is around $60 (2000 CRE * ~$0.03c). This amount clearly has not deterred any of these proposals from going live.

##New Changes

We at Simply Staking are proposing:

* Increase the Minimum Deposit to 7500 CRE. This would increase the value from $60 to $225 for a proposal to go live.
* Decrease the Max Deposit Period down from 5 days to 1 day. This would ensure that any spam proposals would not filter out any useful proposals that might require a deposit.


We are hopeful that the proposed changes will help mitigate the malicious proposals from going live and protect the network participants from putting their funds at risk.

*Please note: We will monitor the price and parameter and adjust in the future if necessary through another governance vote.*

##Voting

* By voting **YES**, you agree that the minimum deposit for a proposal to enter the voting period should be increased from 2000 CRE to 7500 CRE and that the deposit period should be dropped to 1 day.
* By voting **NO**, you disagree that the minimum deposit for a proposal to enter the voting period should be increased from 2000 CRE to 7500 CRE and that the deposit period should be dropped to 1 day.
* By voting **ABSTAIN**, you formally decline to vote either for or against the proposal.
* A **'NoWithVeto'** vote indicates a proposal either (1) is deemed to be spam, i.e., irrelevant to Crescent Network, (2) disproportionately infringes on minority interests, or (3) violates or encourages violation of the rules of engagement as currently set out by Crescent Network governance.

detail.title: Approve Genesis Lab as Crescent Liquid Staking Validator
detail.description:
According to the last announcement for adding a new Liquid Staking Validator, we had got an LSV application form for 2 weeks. Based on the scoring system that we opened and discussed on the commonwealth, we extracted the top 3 candidates out of 9 candidates.

**Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve ‘Genesis Lab’ to be adopted as a new liquid staking validator.**

only YES votes will be counted. Voting NO, NO WITH VETO, or ABSTAIN will have no effect on which candidate is adopted. (However, when the number of the voting amount is significantly different among each candidate, No votes can be reflected)

Voting procedures summary:

- Existing LSV should not vote, and votes by existing LSV will not be counted for this proposal
- Only one candidate that receives the highest number of CRE for ‘Yes’ voting, can only proceed to the next step
- The final validator needs to be agreed upon via on-chain governance(existing LSV need to vote)
- New LSV is added upon the passing of the governance proposal

Link to the docs for all candidates scoring:

: [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TjVh5JWBrF4YM2zxsi1SZXHmDkBXqg-x/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=103096296126293453015&rtpof=true&sd=true](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TjVh5JWBrF4YM2zxsi1SZXHmDkBXqg-x/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=103096296126293453015&rtpof=true&sd=true)

Here’s the scoring system that was discussed before:
: [https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/11043-the-feedback-period-for-lsv-candidates-scoring](https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/11043-the-feedback-period-for-lsv-candidates-scoring)

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by Genesis Lab**

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

:Emergency situations: We completely understand, that blockchains are experimental technologies and it is crucial to be in touch 24/7 for effective and quick issue addressing. Our Prometheus and Grafana-based monitoring system combined with Prometheus alert manager allows us to be aware of the condition of the network around the clock for instant reaction. Governance: We acknowledge importance of the governance process in decentralized systems. We are taking part in all governance activities such as discussing and voting with full responsibility. Community & Marketing: In addition to the Stakeflow explorer ([https://stakeflow.io/](https://stakeflow.io/)) development we have a blog on Medium ([https://blog.stakeflow.io/](https://blog.stakeflow.io/)) and a Twitter ([https://twitter.com/stakeflow](https://twitter.com/stakeflow)) account, where we regularly publish educational posts and articles for the public good. We will be pleased to make materials about the Crescent network for our socials. Other services: We use our own APIs, RPCs, gRPCs for every maintaining blockchain as well as Crescent. We are maintaining IBC relayers between crucial projects of the Cosmos Hub.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

:We are going to provide the best performance and security for the our validator node and infrastructure.

Infra specs and operation specs

:We are using dedicated server for Crescent node and we can use additional dedicated servers for sentry nodes. For monitoring we use Prometheus, Grafana and our custom exporters if needed. We collect metrics by Prometheus node_exporter and visualise at Grafana, also we are using Prometheus alert_manager to get alerts to our Slack channel to react instantly to any problem. We also use ssh access and a firewall on all our servers to ensure security. Our team is available 24/7 in the case of problems with the node.

: We are already self-sustaining

Infra specs and operation specs

: How is the validator key protected? We use a form of Secrets Management, so that the key is encrypted and only available to the validator process. How do you protect your servers? The normal stuff but quick overview: * External hardware firewall & internal software firewall (SSH port has whitelisted ip's) * Automatic security updates * Non-root users (including applications) * Yubikeys + 2FA where possible (SSH, Git, etc) Do you operate sentries? We do not believe this is effective architecture and it just adds latency and complexity which is an enemy; instead we prefer to have many standby backup nodes distributed across many different hardware providers and regions. Do we use Horcrux or Tmkms? Why Secrets Management over HSM? Again similar to the sentries this adds latency and complexity; and we have decided because of this is actually increases risk rather than diminish it; that being said this is still something we think about a lot internally and is under constant consideration. detail.title: Emission change for 2nd year
detail.description:
**Change in Emissions ([Commonwealth Link](https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/10953-discussion-change-in-emissions-for-2nd-year))**

In one of the fastest-moving industries, it is essential to be highly flexible to change, and thus we propose a revision of 2nd-year emissions to the following:

|  | Liquidity Provider | Market Maker | Boost | Ecosystem Reserve | Total |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1st year | 50% | 30% | 50% | 0 | 108.7m CRE |
| 2nd year(OLD) | 20% | 30% | 50% | 0 | 216.1m CRE |
| 2nd Year (Proposed) | 40% | 10% | 40% | 10% | 216.1m CRE |
- LP is still a large part of Crescent’s growth, and liquidity is necessary to launch new utilities. Hence LP incentives will be slightly decreased from current levels, but more than projected at genesis.
- With the implementation of EVM or Cosmwasm imminent, we need incentives to be allocated to 3rd party apps, and the Ecosystem Reserve will serve this purpose (Spent through governance) (**cre180s8gyjtqdczkxuk6xf0r2w3fyln59m6nuuyh8sw3v8kjvjzm0ks7e8jfe**)
- Boost is under the hood, to be revealed to our users soon. And trust us, Boostdrop is also a large part of the design, and long-time supporters of Crescent and its governance token will not be disappointed.

Upon sufficient discussion, a proposal for parameter change will be uploaded. If passed, the emissions for Year 2, starting on April 13th, will follow the new emissions plan.

detail.title: Confirm erasing Dokia Capital from LSV
detail.description:
This is the proposal for erasing Dokia Capital from LSV. As we made an announcement to the community, Dokia had unbonded all tokens and shut down their validator. The action was taken solely by the will of the Dokia capital based on their decision. However, going through the governance proposal is essential for the community to erase the specific validator from Crescent LSV. Therefore, we’d like to make a confirmation proposal to eliminate Dokia Capital from Crescent LSV. 

Voting YES to this proposal means confirming Dokia capital to be erased from Crescent new LSV.

As soon as this proposal pass, Dokia Capital will be erased from Crescent LSV group automatically. For the confirmation proposal, existing LSVs need to participate in voting.

detail.title: Approve Stakely.io as Crescent Liquid Staking Validator
detail.description:
According to the last announcement for adding a new Liquid Staking Validator, we had got an LSV application form for 2 weeks. Based on the scoring system that we opened and discussed on the commonwealth, we extracted the top 3 candidates out of 13 candidates.

**Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve ‘Stakely.io’ to be adopted as a new liquid staking validator.**

only YES votes will be counted. Voting NO, NO WITH VETO, or ABSTAIN will have no effect on which candidate is adopted. (However, when the number of the voting amount is significantly different among each candidate, No votes can be reflected)

Voting procedures summary:

- Existing LSV should not vote, and votes by existing LSV will not be counted for this proposal
- Only one candidate that receives the highest number of CRE for ‘Yes’ voting, can only proceed to the next step
- The final validator needs to be agreed upon via on-chain governance(existing LSV need to vote)
- New LSV is added upon the passing of the governance proposal

Link to the docs for all candidates scoring:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1s8O1O_q_byugOOznhhUPQo9IM2YGxNbG/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=103096296126293453015&rtpof=true&sd=true

Here’s the scoring system that was discussed before:
https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/5199-discussion-liquid-staking-validator-scoring-system

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by Stakely**

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

:We commit to providing detailed and up-to-date information about Crescent on our website, as well as facilitating staking tutorials and tutorials on the main Crescent tools, and answering any major questions that users may have about Crescent, both through our FAQ section and by providing support in our English and Spanish communities. Currently, we provide support and create content in both English and Spanish, but we will open a community in French and translate Crescent-related content into French to also bring Crescent to the French-speaking community. We always vote on all governance proposals and we make all of our community aware by communicating our decisions via Twitter. We also have an RPC/LCD endpoint load balancer service. It aggregates several public and private nodes and the requests are routed among them. This service has many features like health checks, retires on errors and 10s timeouts, CORS-enabled requests, caching, etc. We could integrate Crescent into it if the team thinks it would be helpful. Another service we provide is a multi-coin mainnet faucet, where we currently have Crescent integrated (https://stakely.io/en/faucet/crescent). This service distributes a small amount of mainnet tokens to the users that have run out of gas. It can help bring more people to the project and improve the network's user experience. We will continue maintaining this service and refilling the faucet with our own funds. We can deploy a testnet faucet if needed too.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

:We estimate that the rewards obtained from delegations will be enough to pay for the maintenance of the validator. There are other income sources that we can study, like offering archive RPCs and white-label validators. In case running the validator is not profitable in the future, we have enough income from other networks to continue maintaining it.

Infra specs and operation specs

:Our Crescent validator runs on a bare metal server in Tokyo with the following specifications: CPU: Intel Xeon E-2286G - 6c/12t - 4 GHz/4.9 GHz Memory: 32GB Storage: 2 x 1TB SSD Raid 1 Bandwidth: 1000 Mbps We also have a full-node running for redundancy that we will use in case of any issues. It has the state-sync feature enabled which will help in case we needed to launch a new server. We have previously used tools like TMKMS but we decided to stop using them due to latency. We have also heard about Horcrux in the last months, and we are discussing using it in our setup. We use Prometheus, Zabbix, Grafana, and custom scripts for our monitoring system.

**For more details, qualitative answers can be found here
:**https://docs.google.com/document/d/1F1lxjAP77ZkBdMFH6HMjP7HZGuHFnY05PJfGZdI63bM/edit?usp=sharing ****

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

detail.description:

detail.title: Approve polkachu.com as Crescent Liquid Staking Validator
detail.description:
According to the last announcement for adding a new Liquid Staking Validator, we got an LSV application form for 2 weeks and a feedback period for 1 week. Based on the scoring system that we opened and discussed on the commonwealth, we extracted the top 3 candidates out of 16 candidates. 

In order to align with the principles of blockchain and Cosmos alike, decentralization should be at the heart of Crescent. Therefore, we would like to onboard two validator teams for this round of voting, upon which the two teams with the highest votes will be included in the current LSV, in an effort to further pursue decentralization

For this round, top 2 validators will be added to the LSV governance voting.

Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve ‘[polkachu.com](http://polkachu.com/)’ to be adopted as a new liquid staking validator.

Only YES votes will be counted. Voting NO, NO WITH VETO, or ABSTAIN will have no effect on which candidate is adopted. (However, when the number of the voting amount is significantly different among each candidate, No votes can be reflected)

Voting procedures summary:

- Existing LSV should not vote, and votes by existing LSV will not be counted for this proposal
- Top 2 candidates that receives the highest number of CRE for ‘Yes’ voting, can only proceed to the next step
- The final validator needs to be agreed upon via on-chain governance(existing LSV need to vote)
- New LSV is added upon the passing of the governance proposal

Link to the docs for all candidates scoring:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1C4A0RluUqxR0Qg_n7wd9jrrVFFehVw5l/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=115407576662815838896&rtpof=true&sd=true

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by** [polkachu.com](http://polkachu.com/)

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

: We will continue to run the validation service and expand the IBC channels for Crescent. Will continue to contribute to the open-source projects.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

: We have been sustaining the Crescent node in the active set in the past 6 months flawlessly. We will continue the same top-notch work that we have been doing.

Infra specs and operation specs

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

: In addition to running secure and reliable staking infrastructure for Crescent, Stakin plans to contribute to the Crescent ecosystem on many fronts:
Emergency situations: In the past, we have been available for most technical emergency situations. Blockchains are experimental technologies, and we understand that it is in bad times that proactive validators are the most needed. With 24/7 on-call rotation and monitoring, we will be available for emergency situations at the validator level but also for network-related emergencies.
Governance: vote on all key proposals and join the decentralized governance debate, inviting the community and delegators to contribute as well. Every week we share a weekly governance recap on our different social media platforms (Twitter, Discord), but also discuss proposals. So far we have voted on 100% of Crescent proposals.
Community: we have a dedicated community manager working with the Cosmos ecosystem and Cosmos networks. We will assist the Crescent community with liquid staking, staking requests and join discussions in general.
Marketing: we regularly publish content on our blog (https://blog.stakin.com/) and Medium (https://medium.com/stakin) which attract ~30,000 monthly readers. We believe that education is an important aspect of the growth of DeFi and DeFi products. As such, we will write and share content about Crescent with our community.
Other services: we can operate other services such as Seeds, public RPCs, Snapshots, etc. if needed depending on the requirements of Crescent and the community.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

: We will charge a 20% commission on staking rewards like the other validators that are part of the program.

Infra specs and operation specs

: We are currently running our validator in Tokyo with a sentry node architecture, leveraging multiple cloud providers (GCP, Vultr) for diversity and redundancy. As we are using the cloud, we can increase the specs easily if needed. Currently, we are running with 8 CPUs, 32 GB RAM, and 1TB SSD.

Sentry nodes are connected to the validator in private mode using a VPN tunnel for latency and security. Sentries are open to the public network and keep in sync with the network while providing DDOS protection. For further protection, only required ports are open for both sentries and validators.

The company has a strict role management policy for access to production infrastructure including servers operating sentry nodes and validators.

The developers operate via ZTNA, with strict rules for SSH login and IP whitelists. All accesses are logged and monitored. Infrastructure secrets are encrypted and stored in secure HashiCorp vaults. Credentials, passwords and tokens are generated, stored and rotated from the vault.

Details for this section can be found at the following IPFS link below:

https://ipfs.io/ipfs/QmeBfywbWsTmsU5AkKpaKPmPNSPZP5QVZELjnMRCBFhBQu

detail.title: Crescent V3 Bug Bounty - Crescent Rehearsal and Academy
detail.description:
Crescent is a team that continues a commitment to providing innovative DeFi solutions and public infrastructure. In doing so, we understand that users may require time to familiarize themselves with the novelty and unique traits of DeFi utilities that Crescent Network provides for the Cosmos Ecosystem.
In July, we received various well-analyzed contributions through our first Bug Bounty, of which many were implemented into our mainnet, successfully serving its purpose of retaining security and improving user experience for features never before seen on Cosmos.
We aim to introduce the following utilities in our V3 upgrade on Crescent Network:
Liquid Farming
Market Maker Incentives
Farming Version 2.0
Mobile orderbook UI
In anticipation for the game-changing upgrades of Crescent V3, we would like to invite all users to test new functions prior to launch on the mainnet. As a team that focuses both on DeFi innovations and community engagement alike, we acknowledge the capabilities of our users.
The Crescent Foundation proposes the allocation of 300,000 CRE from the Community Fund to be utilized in a Bug Bounty on the Crescent testnet. This will make sure that those actively participating in the improvement of our network will be accurately rewarded.
The Crescent Rehearsal will commence on November 24, lasting until December 1, during which time users will be able to submit feedback and content of the following categories:
Bug Bounty:
Submitted via the Crescent Bug Reporting Form (To be provided at the beginning of testnet)
Critical: 50000 CRE
• Exploitation of liquidity, chain halting, stolen funds, token inflation bug
Major: 5000 CRE
Liquid Farming, Market Maker Incentives, and Farming V2 specific core bug other than Critical bug, limited financial exploitation
Minor: 200 CRE
Judged case-by-case
Note that MOST front-end bugs will be categorized as Minor unless deemed critical to the network
The rewarding will be based on first-report-first-reward basis, with repeated and already reported bugs being ineligible for rewarding.
The rewarding of each eligible case will be reviewed by the Foundation and presented to the community through governance upon completion of the Bug Bounty. Upon passing of the proposal, each eligible user will be rewarded their corresponding CRE for their contribution to development of secure utilities.
In the case of a bug being reported and scored among the eligible criteria(Criteria below), the user will be rewarded via the Foundation’s multi-sig wallet(cre1u9jxn6l7seq5jjej4w6etpdxufphwfuunljr4e), which will receive and distribute the bug bounty rewards, and the remaining funds will be returned to the Community Fund. 

Crescent Academy(Utility Education): 
In order to promote a community culture of shared educational and entertainment content,we will start the implementation of the Crescent Academy. 
The purpose of this school is to allow people involved in educational content creation to participate in the evolution of Crescent and the education of the newcomers. 
The goal here is to make content easy to understand and available for everyone who joins our community. These contents can be: 
Youtube videos
Twitter threads
Medium articles
Etc. 
These contents should talk about the testnet and what V3 upgrade will introduce: 
Liquid Farming 
Market Maker Incentives 
Farming Version 2.0 
Mobile orderbook UI 
the goal is not to make a simple article, but especially to make complete contents, well explained such as: 
Tutorial 
Liquid Farming explanation 
Comparison between what we know and the new Crescent model 
And more. 
We expect rich content with images, a clear editorial line and a fluid flow. 
The reward of each eligible case will be reviewed by the Foundation and presented to the community on discord. 
You will be limited to one piece of content per user, so take the time to choose it and polish it. You will have to submit your content using Crew3 and your review will be pending until the end of the bug bounty. 
Each eligible user will be rewarded their corresponding CRE for their contribution to development of the Crescent school.
Note that the school will not only last during the bug bounty period, it will be part of Crescent structure.

detail.title: Reallocation of LP farming plan - Incentivize INJ / bCRE pool
detail.description:
This governance proposal is to initiate reallocation of the current farming plan to accommodate a newly created pool.

As discussed through the Crescent Forum, both Crescent and Injective see synergy in merging of communities and allowing the onboarding of native tokens on each respective DEX. Through the listing of Injective’s $INJ, Crescent can expect the merge of communities and user flow from the Injective protocol.

The farming weights are always up for discussion, and will be adjusted to include newly launched tokens that have potential for synergy with Crescent DEX in the future according to governance and user demand.

INJ listing forum discussion: https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/7669-injective-protocol-inj

The Crescent Foundation proposes the following farming weights below in consideration of newly listed assets, and capital-efficiency of ranged pools:

- **Newly Incentivized Farming Pools**
    - INJ / bCRE Ranged Pool (5.0~60.0) : 6%
- **Farming Weight Adjustment**
- Reserve(Module Account): 23% > 17%
    - To be utilized in the incentivization of newly listed tokens
- **Unchanged Farming Weights**
    - ATOM / USDC.axl: 10%
    - ATOM / USDC.grv: 10%
    - USDC.axl / USDC.grv Ranged Pool (0.99~1.01): 2%
    - ATOM/bCRE (Basic Pool): 20%
    - ATOM / bCRE Ranged Pool (20~100): 15%
    - GRAV / bCRE Ranged Pool (0.03~0.20): 3%
    - bCRE / CRE (Basic Pool): 10%
    - bCRE / CRE Ranged Pool (1.15~1.25): 5%
    - IST / USDC.axl (0.99~1.01): 1%
    - IST / USDC.grv (0.99~1.01): 1%

detail.description:
According to the last announcement for adding a new Liquid Staking Validator, we got an LSV application form for 2 weeks and a feedback period for 1 week. Based on the scoring system that we opened and discussed on the commonwealth, we extracted the top 3 candidates out of 20 candidates.

Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve ‘Smart Stake’ to be adopted as a new liquid staking validator.

Only YES votes will be counted. Voting NO, NO WITH VETO, or ABSTAIN will have no effect on which candidate is adopted. (However, when the number of the voting amount is significantly different among each candidate, No votes can be reflected)

Voting procedures summary:

- Existing LSV should not vote, and votes by existing LSV will not be counted for this proposal
- Only one candidate that receives the highest number of CRE for ‘Yes’ voting, can only proceed to the next step
- The final validator needs to be agreed upon via on-chain governance(existing LSV need to vote)
- New LSV is added upon the passing of the governance proposal

Link to the docs for all candidates scoring:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1iG5QVLldbaVVWRLVvddoQaNLiLJXbs04/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=115407576662815838896&rtpof=true&sd=true

Here’s the scoring system that was discussed before: https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/6614-amended-scoring-system-for-adding-new-lsv

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by Smart Stake**

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

: Smart Stake has built a basic analytics dashboard for Crescent at crescent.smartstake.io and also provided support for Crescent in its decentralization metrics comparison dashboard at [decentralization.smartstake.io](http://decentralization.smartstake.io/) / [d14n.smartstake.io](http://d14n.smartstake.io/). The current dashboard has validator performance history, calculator, network statistics, governance participation /proposals. We have plans to build 10+ more features in the current dashboard. As the community evolves and it has more specific needs, we will build more tools. Smart Stake's custom analytics provide answers to common questions of the community and is looking forward to help improve the engagement level in Crescent.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

: Smart Stake has only one source of revenue (commission from staking rewards). It will continue to support the Crescent validator from its commission from other networks and looks forward to inclusion in LSV for covering Crescent nodes expenses eventually.

Infra specs and operation specs

: Smart Stake hardens every server node with a standard setup where root access is removed, ssh keys are used for authentication, firewalls are installed, failban is used to limit unwanted access attempts. All validator nodes have a corresponding hot backup of all validators. For networks requiring high throughput, we do not use sentry node architecture unless needed for a particular project or where the threat vectors are higher. We use custom scripting to watch for server metrics, node performance, node sync status, signs missed, oracle performance. Pagerduty workflows are also in place to place calls/sms/push notifications whenever anomalies are detected. The scripting has several failsafe mechanisms built in to ensure if the scripting fails, that itself generates alerts.

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by** [Stakely.io](http://stakely.io/)

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

: We will promote Crescent in our Spanish communities and will support it through our social media, besides publishing staking guides, video tutorials, SEO-optimized posts, and other educational content in different languages to help our community to understand what Crescent is and how to stake. We always vote on all governance proposals and we make all of our community aware by communicating our decisions via Twitter. We also have an RPC/LCD endpoint load balancer service. It aggregates several public and private nodes and the requests are routed among them. This service has many features like health checks, retires on errors and 10s timeouts, CORS-enabled requests, caching, etc. We could integrate Crescent into it if the team thinks it would be helpful. Another service we provide is a multi-coin mainnet faucet, where we currently have Crescent integrated (https://stakely.io/en/faucet/crescent). This service distributes a small amount of mainnet tokens to the users that have run out of gas. It can help bring more people to the project and improve the network's user experience. We will continue maintaining this service and refilling the faucet with our own funds. As an additional contribution, we are planning to build Docker images for most of the Cosmos-based chains, including Crescent.

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

: We estimate that the rewards obtained from delegations will be enough to pay for the maintenance of the validator. There are other income sources that we can study, like offering archive RPCs and white-label validators. In case running the validator is not profitable in the future, we have enough income from other networks to continue maintaining it.

Infra specs and operation specs

:Our Crescent validator runs in a bare metal server in Tokyo with the following specifications: CPU: Intel Xeon E-2286G - 6c/12t - 4 GHz/4.9 GHz Memory: 32GB Storage: 2 x 1TB SSD Raid 1 Bandwidth: 1000 Mbps We also have a full-node running for redundancy that we will use in case of any issues. It has the state-sync feature enabled which will help in case we needed to launch a new server. We have previously used tools like TMKMS but we decided to stop using them due to latency. We have also heard about Horcrux in the last months, and we are discussing using it in our setup. We use Prometheus, Zabbix, Grafana, and custom bash-scripts for our monitoring system. Prometheus sends us data from the system and node to Zabbix, where we manage the notifications and alerts for system metrics Grafana is used for visual metrics of server and node historical data Custom bash scripts for alerts like node not-in-sync, low number of peers, high system usage, missed blocks, etc. that notifies us in our private Discord server.

Details for this section can be found at the following IPFS link below.

https://ipfs.io/ipfs/QmPxaSYSvTKdo12ZmJ2EubEhrvyTWVp78ahjiN9A9fvGqe

detail.title: Signal Proposal: Farming Plan Reallocation
detail.description:
Reallocation of LP farming and creation of new pools

This governance proposal is to initiate reallocation of the current farming plan to include newly created pools and fully utilize the potential of ranged pools for maximum efficiency in trading experience.

The current farming plan has increased both liquidity and TVL within Crescent DEX. As can be seen by the existing ranged pools, the liquidity of ranged pools are amplified beyond that of basic pools, giving reason for migrating major pairs to implement range. Also, in the Crescent spirit of maximizing utility and efficiency of trading, certain pools have shown no use-cases, exposing reason for being faded out.

Realizing the capital-efficiency and liquidity amplification of ranged pools and orderbook, we must take into consideration of many new major tokens being launched on the Cosmos Ecosystem, and creating a sustainable market for them. According to the Crescent Ethos, our DEX will continue liquidity incubation for major tokens by utilizing our superior utilities.

The farming weights are always up for discussion, and will be adjusted to include newly launched tokens that have potential for synergy with Crescent DEX in the future according to governance and user demand.

The Foundation proposes the following farming weights below in consideration of newly listed assets, and capital-efficiency of ranged pools:

- **Newly Incentivized Farming Pools**
    - ATOM / bCRE Ranged Pool (20~100): 15%
        - This pair has shown a relatively stable price range during the duration of its existence, giving reason to believe that a ranged pool is possible and will provide a better trading experience through liquidity amplification
    - BLD / bCRE Ranged Pool (1.0~7.0): 3%
        - Given the proposed price range, BLD / bCRE pair’s liquidity will be amplified, requiring less TVL for the same trading experience when compared to basic AMM of other DEXs
        - Farming rewards will commence for 28 days from implementation
    - GRAV / bCRE Ranged Pool (0.03~0.20): 3%
        - Continued partnership with Gravity Bridge and expanded implementation of the team’s technology within Crescent DEX (Gravity Bridge to propose renewal of private GRAV incentives)
    - bCRE / CRE Ranged Pool (1.10~1.20): 5%
        - Introduction of a smaller farming weight for this pool, and will monitor TVL changes and adjust according to user demand
- **Farming Weight Adjustment**
    - bCRE / CRE (Basic Pool): 20% > 10%
        - Will possibly be replaced with ranged pool as the price discrepancy is predictable
    - ATOM/bCRE (Basic Pool): 35% > 20%
        - Possible migration to ranged pool, will monitor changes in TVL and liquidity to adjust accordingly
    - Reserve(Module Account): 5% > 17%
        - To be utilized in the incentivization of newly listed tokens
- **Discontinuation of Farming Rewards**
    - bCRE / USDC.axl: 5% > 0%
        - Small trade volume, and can be replaced by multi-hop swap through ATOM
    - bCRE / USDC.grv: 5% > 0%
        - Same as above
    - ETH.axl / ETH.grv Ranged Pool(±1%): 2% > 0%
        - Relatively small trade volume, and does not have a practical use-case for Crescent DEX
    - GRAV / bCRE (Basic Pool): 1% > 0%
        - Replaced by Ranged Pool above for more efficient liquidity
- **Unchanged Farming Weights**
    - ATOM / USDC.axl: 10%
    - ATOM / USDC.grv: 10%
    - USDC.axl / USDC.grv Ranged Pool (0.99~1.01): 2%
    - bCRE / CRE Ranged Pool (1.063~1.15): 5%
- **Note**
    - Market Maker Incentives will be implemented for WBTC, ETH, ATOM / USDC pairs in the coming months

detail.title: 3SO, immediate kick-out governance proposal
detail.description:
**3 Strike Out & immediate kick-out policy adoption**

This on-chain governance proposal is to adopt 3 Strike Out & immediate kick-out policy. 

Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve 3 Strike Out & immediate kick-out policy adoption, following details are as below:

3Strike Out(3SO)

- Stability

Block missing percentage over 10% every week

- Sustainability

Take over 6-hours in succession without block signing

- Reliability

When validator meets 2 items out of 3, they will get 1 strike

Binary upgrade in 3 hours (related to software), Emergency response in 12 hours, Node config upgrade in 24 hours (related with local setting ex, block time control, node parameter)

- Engagement

When the validator does not participate in governance actively, Crescent foundation gives a warning. If the validator does not vote even validator gets a warning, they will can 1 strike. Or, If a specific validator’s voting rate is less than 50% since they join LSV. Or when specific validator votes ‘abstain’ habitually in succession

- Performance (https://bit.ly/3bLUeAQ)

When proposing Diff(the actual number of proposing blocks compared with voting power) is less than 90% with 2 months of data, the validator gets 1 strike

- Activity (https://bit.ly/3bLUeAQ)

Based on the data we extract every 2 months when a specific validator’s Expected TX share(actual handled TX is divided by expected TX) is less than 50%, that validator gets 1 strike.

Immediate Kick-Out

- set commission rate higher than 20% over 3 days totally(accumulative)
- Censorship/manipulation on mempool 
- When specific validator censors and then picks or excludes specific transactions in order to get profit
- Private Transaction Broadcasting
- When the validator handles the specific transaction without letting other validators know
- Double signing tombstone (not conducted through governance, will be immediately eliminated by code)

You can check community discussion for **3 Strike Out & immediate kick-out** here**:** 

https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/5983-validator-3-strike-out-immediate-kickout-discussion

detail.title: Reallocation of LP farming plan to include ranged pools
detail.description:
Reallocation of LP farming plan to include ranged pools

This governance proposal is to initiate reallocation of the current farming plan to accommodate newly created pools and bootstrap ranged liquidity, as part of Crescent Network’s vision of capital-efficient and sustainable liquidity.

The current farming plan consists heavily on the: ATOM/bCRE, and bCRE/CRE pairs, with minimal incentives allocated to pairs with bridged assets. The plan secured liquidity in the native assets of Crescent Network and the Cosmos Ecosystem.

With the introduction of ranged liquidity on Crescent DEX, the farming weights need to be adjusted to accurately reward liquidity providers, create investment alternatives through ranged pools, and ultimately establish sufficient liquidity in pools that will synergize with Crescent Boost. In the case of the bCRE/CRE pool, the amplification of a user’s provided liquidity will be appx. 54X, and for ETH/ETH and USDC/USDC, 200X, resulting in more effective liquidity within the set range of the pools.

As stated in the Crescent Ethos, the network will focus on stable and major tokens, with this allocation plan to vitalize ATOM and USDC, which are key assets as well as pools such as ATOM/USDC to be used in Crescent Boost by becoming the target pairs of the new upcoming utility. ETH liquidity will be more available for trading through Market Maker incentives in October, and expanded investment opportunities once key utilities are firmly established.

The proposed reallocation of farming weights is as below:

- Newly Incentivized Farming Pools
    - bCRE / CRE Ranged Pool (1.063~1.15): 5%
    - ATOM / USDC.axl: 10%
    - ATOM / USDC.grv: 10%
    - ETH.axl / ETH.grv Ranged Pool(±1%): 2%
    - USDC.axl / USDC.grv Ranged Pool(±1%): 2%
    - GRAV / bCRE: 1% (For 50 days from passing of proposal)
- Farming Weight Adjustment
    - bCRE / CRE: 25% > 20%
    - bCRE / USDC.axl: 1% > 5%
    - bCRE / USDC.grv: 1% > 5%
    - WETH.axl / bCRE: 1% > 0%
    - WETH.grv / bCRE 1% > 0%
    - Module Account: 36% > 5%

detail.title: Community Fund Spend Proposal - Bug Bounty
detail.description:
In alignment with Crescent Network’s principle of smoothly onboarding users, the necessity for testing new utilities is apparent. Keeping in mind that in an ecosystem flooded by traditional AMM DEXs, Crescent aims to provide a hybrid trading experience that synergizes AMM and orderbook.

With the imminent launch of orderbook and ranged liquidity UI, the foundation will invite users to test and get to know Crescent’s new utilities through the mooncat-1-1 testnet. When the testnet is opened publicly, users can experience the innovative feature before its debut on mainnet.

Being a core function of Crescent DEX, and one that is highly anticipated by users, we want to incorporate the community in the road to a perfect orderbook and ranged liquidity that can be utilized smoothly by all.

As a team that always prioritizes user safety and the integrity of the network, we would like users’ feedback, both on an experience basis, as well as technical. With that, we propose the allocation of 100,000 CRE from the Community Fund to be utilized in a Bug Bounty on the Crescent testnet. This will make sure that those actively participating in the improvement of our network will be accurately rewarded.

In the case of a bug being reported and scored among the eligible criteria(Criteria below), the user will be rewarded via the Foundation’s multi-sig wallet(cre1u9jxn6l7seq5jjej4w6etpdxufphwfuunljr4e), which will receive and distribute the bug bounty rewards, and the remaining funds will be returned to the Community Fund. The distribution of each rewarded case will be reported to the community for clarity and visibility.

Users participating in the testnet can report found bugs through the Bug Reporting Form (To be announced upon opening of public testnet), upon which it will be categorized and judged by the Foundation according to the level of importance stated below:

- Critical: 20,000 CRE
    - Exploitation of liquidity, chain halting, stolen funds, token inflation bug
- Major: 5000 CRE
    - Orderbook specific core bug other than Critical bug, limited financial exploitation
- Minor:  500 CRE
    - Judged case-by-case
    - *Note that MOST front-end bugs will be categorized as Minor unless deemed critical to the network

The rewarding will be based on first-come-first serve, and repeated or already reported bugs will not be rewarded again.

As always, the Crescent Network team always appreciates the participation of the vibrant community, and we would like to continue building together for a prolonged sustainable and secure service for Cosmonauts and beyond. Through the cooperative testing between the dev team and our great community, we will work towards orderbook and ranged liquidity UI that have smooth UX with airtight security.

detail.title: Approve Citadel.one as Crescent Liquid Staking Validator
detail.description:
According to the last announcement for adding a new Liquid Staking Validator, we had got an LSV application form for 2 weeks. Based on the scoring system that we opened and discussed on the commonwealth, we extracted the top 3 candidates out of 27 candidates.

**Voting YES to this proposal means that you approve ‘Citadel.one’ to be adopted as a new liquid staking validator.** 

only YES votes will be counted. Voting NO, NO WITH VETO, or ABSTAIN will have no effect on which candidate is adopted. (However, when the number of the voting amount is significantly different among each candidate, No votes can be reflected)

Voting procedures summary:

- Existing LSV should not vote, and votes by existing LSV will not be counted for this proposal
- Only one candidate that receives the highest number of CRE for ‘Yes’ voting, can only proceed to the next step
- The final validator needs to be agreed upon via on-chain governance(existing LSV need to vote)
- New LSV is added upon the passing of the governance proposal

Link to the docs for all candidates scoring: 

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/14CPUXiIWXSVvW2HR7E3VVRjPjjKCVW_W/edit?usp=sharing&ouid=113404813873563669465&rtpof=true&sd=true

Here’s the scoring system that was discussed before: 
https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/5199-discussion-liquid-staking-validator-scoring-system

**Qualitative Scoring Criteria submitted by Citadel.one**

How will you contribute to the Crescent Ecosystem in the future?

:Integration into Citadel.one platform, marketing, educational page, governance application

What is your long-term plan to sustain the Crescent node?

:Advanced technical monitoring for sustaining the tech side + growing the community

Infra specs and operation specs

:We use advanced tooling to make sure everything is running smoothly on our validator side

1) Grafana for monitoring of our nodes' CPU load, uptime, current and missed blocks and random-access memory usage.
2) ELK Stack software for building analytics, errors search, failure mode and effects analysis.
3) Zabbix for hardware, hard disk and memory load monitoring.
4) just in case - Telegram bot that sends notifications if something out of order occurs.

detail.title: Reallocation of LP Farming Plan to include minimal incentives of bridged assets
detail.description:
1. Introduction
    
    This governance proposal is to launch initial minimal farming reward for bridge assets from Axelar and Gravity Bridge. Incentivized assets include ETH and USDC.
    
    Crescent Network would like to adopt assets from the bridges to provide users more variety of options for trading and LP investment.
    
    However, because the security of both bridges are not fully reviewed by Crescent Team yet, the amount of farming rewards for these assets will be relatively small, until we have enough confidence on the security of the bridges in the future.
    
    The newly incentivized pools are a result of the previously announced community discussion that took place at Crescent Network Commonwealth for 7 days. The key takeaway was to introduce and implement incentives to the ETH / bCRE pool in addition to the proposed bCRE / USDC pool.
    
    Reasoning for the immediate incentivization and consideration of other bridged assets can be found at the Commonwealth Proposal Discussion:
    
    https://commonwealth.im/crescent-forum/discussion/4962-minimal-incentivization-of-bridged-assets
    
2. Farming Plans
    - New Assets on UI
        - ETH.a : ETH from Axelar
        - USDC.a : USDC from Axelar
        - ETH.g : ETH from Gravity Bridge
        - USDC.g : USDC from Gravity Bridge
    
    - Newly Incentivized Farming Pools
        - bCRE / USDC.axl : 1%
        - bCRE / USDC.grv : 1%
        - ETH.axl / bCRE : 1%
        - ETH.grv / bCRE : 1%
    
    - Existing Incentivized Farming Pools and Module Account
        - CRE / bCRE : 25%
        - ATOM / bCRE : 35%
        - Module Account : 36%
        
        The module account will continue to be released to newly introduced pools in the near future for increased incentivization to migrate liquidity from external blockchains.
        
3. Reasoning
    - Bridges
        - Most active bridges in Cosmos Ecosystem
        - Active partnership under progress with Crescent Team
        - Minimum necessary evidence of security is satisfied
    - Assets
        - ETH
            - The most popular asset for many DeFi products
            - Having the second biggest market capital in crypto
        - USDC
            - Stable coin with 100% backed by fiat
            - Most secure stable coin with no significant systemic risk
    - Minimal Amount of Initial Farming (1% farming weight each)
        - Initial farming rewards will be minimal because the security of both bridges are not fully reviewed by Crescent Team yet
        - We will suggest higher farming rewards for the bridge assets when the team has stronger confidence in both bridge technologies
        
4. Future Plans
    - for bCRE / ETH pools
        - gradually increase the farming rewards to form deeper liquidity once security and ecosystem contribution of bridged assets are assessed
    - for ETH / ETH & USDC / USDC pools
        - **in June :** farming rewards will be migrated to “**Ranged LP**” to provide significantly amplified liquidity from smaller TVL
    - for ETH / USDC pools
        - **in July :**  large liquidity will be provided into orderbook when “**Market Maker Incentive**” alive

5. Considerations
    - The assets from both bridges are not fully reviewed by Crescent Team yet.
    - Security risk upon each bridge should be fully acknowledged who decides to possess such assets in Crescent Network.

detail.title: Signalling Proposal for Expanding Pools displayed on UI
detail.description:
This proposal is for the display of bridged assets on Crescent DEX in an effort to expand pool alternatives for users. 
  
 The UI whitelisting of the pools below DOES NOT correlate to a native token incentivization. As stated in the Crescent Ethos, incentivization of bridged assets will be done in a conservative manner, with in-depth, thorough research of the bridge’s security, ecosystem involvement, and capability for expanded interchain functionalities. 
  
 If passed, Crescent DEX will create a pair and pool, as well as display the following assets in the UI: 
  
- USDC (Bridged via Axelar and Gravity Bridge) 
- ETH (Bridged via Axelar and Gravity Bridge) 
- Other native tokens 
  
 The UI whitelisting of the aforementioned pools provides the following for Crescent Network: 
  
- An alternate stablecoin option to utilize 
- Bridged assets from ETH market for future integration into Crescent utilities 
  
 The Foundation will continue research and evaluation of the bridges above before proposing native token incentivization of additional pools.

detail.title: Reallocation of LP farming plan
detail.description:
This proposal is to approve reallocation of current LP farming rewards of Terra’s LUNA and UST paired pools in preemptive action for introducing new pool pairs in the near future. 
  
 The grounds for decision making are as follows: 
  
- LUNA and UST pool incentivizations were implemented to invite liquidity from Terra, which maintained its position as a core Cosmos Ecosystem. Due to unfortunate circumstances, the current tokenomics of UST have created reason for providing investment alternatives for users of Crescent. 
- As of now, LUNA, a representative token of the Terra Ecosystem, has a probability of no longer maintaining an ecosystem that presents a stable coin functionality for Crescent DEX. 
- As can be observed by the extreme APR hike on said pools, Terra-based pools have significantly decreased in investment demand and prolonged allocation of LP incentives to LUNA and UST pools present degraded efficiency of liquidity and rewards allocation. 
  
 If passed, Liquidity Pool Pairs and their farming weights will be adjusted to the below: 
  
- bCRE / CRE: 25% 
- bCRE / UST: 0% 
- ATOM / bCRE: 35% 
- LUNA / bCRE: 0% 
- ATOM / UST: 0% 
- LUNA / UST: 0% 
- Module Account: 40% 
  
 In order to expand the integration of pool pairs that will benefit Crescent Network, the unrewarded LP farming rewards of the LUNA and UST pools will be accumulated in a module account, which can be released to newly introduced pools in the near future for increased incentivization to migrate liquidity from external blockchains. 
  
 Under the guidance of the community approved Crescent Ethos, the foundation will continue extensive research into alternative assets to be integrated into Crescent DEX.
